Introduction to matplotlib¶

Contains material from:

  • The matplotlib tutorial and user guide at http://matplotlib.org/.

Panos Louridas, Associate Professor
Department of Management Science and Technology
Athens University of Economics and Business
louridas@aueb.gr

  • matplotlib is the base visualization library in Python.

  • It is highly customizable and can be used to produce pretty much any kind of graph.

  • At the same time it may require a lot of work to produce graphs that look nice and customization may require fiddling with lots of little details.

  • Everything in matplotlib is organized in a hierarchy.

  • At the top of the hierarchy is the matplotlib "state-machine environment" which is provided by the matplotlib.pyplot module.

  • At this level, simple functions are used to add plot elements (lines, images, text, etc.) to the current axes in the current figure.

  • The next level down in the hierarchy is the first level of the object-oriented interface, in which pyplot is used only for a few functions such as figure creation, and the user explicitly creates and keeps track of the figure and axes objects.

  • At this level, the user uses pyplot to create figures, and through those figures, one or more axes objects can be created. These axes objects are then used for most plotting actions.

  • For even more control which is essential for things like embedding matplotlib plots in GUI applications the pyplot level may be dropped completely, leaving a purely object-oriented approach.

Figure¶

  • The whole figure (marked as the outer red box).

  • The figure keeps track of all the child Axes, a smattering of "special" artists (titles, figure legends, etc), and the canvas.

  • A figure can have any number of Axes, but to be useful it should have at least one.

  • The easiest way to create a new figure is with pyplot:

fig = plt.figure()  # an empty figure with no axes
fig, ax_lst = plt.subplots(2, 2)  # a figure with a 2x2 grid of Axes

Axes¶

This is what you think of as "a plot", it is the region of the image with the data space (marked as the inner blue box).

  • A given figure can contain many Axes, but a given Axes object can only be in one Figure.

  • The Axes contains two (or three in the case of 3D) Axis objects (be aware of the difference between Axes and Axis).

  • Each Axes has a title (set via set_title()), an x-label (set via set_xlabel()), and a y-label (set via set_ylabel()).

Axis¶

  • These are the number-line-like objects (circled in green).

  • They take care of the data limits (the data limits can also be controlled via set via the set_xlim() and set_ylim() Axes methods).

  • They also take care of setting the graph limits and generating the ticks (the marks on the axis) and ticklabels (strings labeling the ticks).

  • The location of the ticks is determined by a Locator object and the ticklabel strings are formatted by a Formatter.

  • The combination of the correct Locator and Formatter gives very fine control over the tick locations and labels.

Artist¶

  • Basically everything you can see on the figure is an artist (even the Figure, Axes, and Axis objects).

  • This includes Text objects, Line2D objects, collection objects, Patch objects...

  • When the figure is rendered, all of the artists are drawn to the canvas.

  • Most Artists are tied to an Axes; such an Artist cannot be shared by multiple Axes, or moved from one to another.

Working with pyplot¶

  • pyplot allows us to add plot elements without having to access Figure and Axes objects.
In [1]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

%matplotlib inline

x = np.linspace(0, 2, 100)

plt.plot(x, x, label='linear')
plt.plot(x, x**2, label='quadratic')
plt.plot(x, x**3, label='cubic')

plt.xlabel('x label')
plt.ylabel('y label')

plt.title("Simple Plot")

plt.legend()

Working with Legends (and Multiple Plots)¶

  • As everything else in matplotlib, legends are highly customizable.

  • In the above example, there is a slight problem in that the legend overlaps with part of the lines.

  • The location of the legend can be set with the loc parameter, which can taken the following values.

Location String Location Code
'best' 0
'upper right' 1
'upper left' 2
'lower left' 3
'lower right' 4
'right' 5
'center left' 6
'center right' 7
'lower center' 8
'upper center' 9
'center' 10

  • We can check that in practice, by creating 10 different plots and seeing where the legend goes for different values of the loc parameter.

  • To create subplots, we use the subplot method. It is usually called as subplot(nrows, ncols, plot_number):

    • nrows is the number of rows
    • ncols is the number of columns
    • plot_number is the number of the plot (which must be between 1 <= plot_number <= nrows * ncols).

  • Depending on what we put in our subplots, they may be cluttered. The spacing can be adjusted with the subplots_adjust(left=None, bottom=None, right=None, top=None, wspace=None, hspace=None) method. The meaning and the default values of the parameters is as follows:

    • left = 0.125: the left side of the subplots of the figure
    • right = 0.9: the right side of the subplots of the figure
    • bottom = 0.1: the bottom of the subplots of the figure
    • top = 0.9: the top of the subplots of the figure
    • wspace = 0.2: the amount of width reserved for blank space between subplots
    • hspace = 0.2: the amount of height reserved for white space between subplots

Colors and Colormaps¶

  • Commands that take color arguments can use several formats to specify the colors. There are eight built-in colors, for which you can use a single letter.
    • b: blue
    • g: green
    • r: red
    • c: cyan
    • m: magenta
    • y: yellow
    • k: black
    • w: white
In [7]:
color = [
    'b',
    'g',
    'r',
    'c',
    'm',
    'y',
    'k',
    'w'
]

figure = plt.figure(figsize=(12, 24))
figure.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.4)

x = np.linspace(-1, 1, 100)
y = x * np.sin(1 / x)

for loc in range(0, 8):
    ax = figure.add_subplot(4, 2, loc + 1)
    ax.plot(x, y, color=color[loc], label=r'$y = x \sin(1/x)$')
    
    ax.set_xlabel('x label')
    ax.set_ylabel('y label')

    ax.set_title("Simple Plot, color set at " + color[loc])

    ax.legend(loc='best')
  • Other ways to specify colors:
    • Gray shades can be given as a string encoding a float in the 0-1 range, e.g.: color = '0.75'.
    • Colors can be specified using an html hex string, as in: color = '#eeefff'
    • Colors can also be specified by passing an R, G, B tuple, where each of R, G, B are in the range [0,1].
    • Finally, legal html names for colors, like 'red', 'burlywood' and 'chartreuse' are supported.

  • Colors can also be selected from colormaps.

  • There are three classes of colormaps:

    • Sequential: change in lightness and often saturation of color incrementally, often using a single hue; should be used for representing information that has ordering.
    • Diverging: change in lightness and possibly saturation of two different colors that meet in the middle at an unsaturated color; should be used when the information being plotted has a critical middle value, such as topography or when the data deviates around zero.
    • Qualitative: often are miscellaneous colors; should be used to represent information which does not have ordering or relationships.

  • The following cmaps list contains tuples of the form ('Colormap Category', [colormap_1, colormap_2, colormap_3]).

  • To display them, we'll use a gradient array for each colormap.

  • Each gradient array will contain two 256 equally-spaced points in the values from 0 to 1 (inclusive).

  • That's because colormaps also have a 256-value resolution.

  • We'll use the numpy.vstack function that stacks arrays vertically (row wise).

In [9]:
gradient = np.linspace(0, 1, 256)
gradient = np.vstack((gradient, gradient))
In [10]:
nrows = max(len(cmap_list) for cmap_category, cmap_list in cmaps)

def plot_color_gradients(cmap_category, cmap_list):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=nrows)
    fig.subplots_adjust(top=0.95, bottom=0.01, left=0.2, right=0.99)
    axes[0].set_title(cmap_category + ' colormaps', fontsize=14)

    for ax, name in zip(axes, cmap_list):
        ax.imshow(gradient, aspect='auto', cmap=plt.get_cmap(name))
        pos = list(ax.get_position().bounds)
        x_text = pos[0] - 0.01
        y_text = pos[1] + pos[3]/2.
        fig.text(x_text, y_text, name, va='center', ha='right', fontsize=10)

    # Turn off *all* ticks & spines, not just the ones with colormaps.
    for ax in axes:
        ax.set_axis_off()

for cmap_category, cmap_list in cmaps:
    plot_color_gradients(cmap_category, cmap_list)

  • Once we have selected a colormap, we can map values to colors based on the colormap.

  • Since colormaps have values between 1 and 256, the values we want to map to colors must be normalized to the same range.

Creating a Correlation Plot with matplotlib¶

  • A correlation plot shows, for a set of variables, the correlations between any pair of variables from the set.

  • An informative correlation plot should show:

    • The correlation between each pair.
    • Whether the correlation is positive or negative.
    • Whether the correlation is statistically significant.

  • We'll write a function that will draw such plots.

  • The function will be called corrplot and will be called like: corrplot(data, pvalues, labels).

    • data is the correlation matrix, a 2D numpy array containing the pairwise correlations between variables.
    • pvalues is a matrix containing the p-value for each corresponding correlation value.
    • labels is an array containing the variable names.
In [11]:
import matplotlib.cm as cm
from matplotlib.patches import Ellipse

def corrplot(data, pvalues, labels):
    """Creates a correlation plot of the passed data.
    The function returns the plot which can then be shown with
    plot.show(), saved to a file with plot.savefig(), or manipulated
    in any other standard matplotlib way.
    data is the correlation matrix, a 2-D numpy array containing
    the pairwise correlations between variables;
    pvalues is a matrix containing the pvalue for each corresponding
    correlation value; if none it is assumed to be the zero matrix
    labels is an array containing the variable names
    """

    plt.figure(1)

    column_labels = labels
    row_labels = labels
    
    ax = plt.subplot(1, 1, 1, aspect='equal')

    width, height = data.shape
    num_cols, num_rows = width, height

    if pvalues is None:
        pvalues = np.zeros([num_rows, num_cols])
        
    shrink = 0.9

    poscm = cm.get_cmap('Blues')
    negcm = cm.get_cmap('Oranges')

    for x in range(width):
        for y in range(height):
            d = data[x, y]
            c = pvalues[x, y]
            rotate = -45 if d > 0 else +45
            clrmap = poscm if d >= 0 else negcm
            d_abs = np.abs(d)
            ellipse = Ellipse((x, y),
                              width=1 * shrink,
                              height=(shrink - d_abs*shrink),
                              angle=rotate)
            ellipse.set_edgecolor('black')
            ellipse.set_facecolor(clrmap(d_abs))
            if c > 0.05:
                ellipse.set_linestyle('dotted')
            ax.add_artist(ellipse)

    ax.set_xlim(-1, num_cols)
    ax.set_ylim(-1, num_rows)
        
    ax.xaxis.tick_top()
    xtickslocs = np.arange(len(row_labels))
    ax.set_xticks(xtickslocs)
    ax.set_xticklabels(row_labels, rotation=30, fontsize='small', ha='left')

    ax.invert_yaxis()
    ytickslocs = np.arange(len(row_labels))
    ax.set_yticks(ytickslocs)
    ax.set_yticklabels(column_labels, fontsize='small')

    return plt

In [13]:
import scipy

corr_matrix = np.corrcoef(randhie_df.T)

(num_rows, num_columns) = randhie_df.shape

corr_matrix = np.eye(num_columns)
p_values = np.zeros([num_rows, num_columns])

for i in range(num_columns):
    for j in range(i+1, num_columns):
        (r, p) = scipy.stats.pearsonr(randhie_df.iloc[:,i], randhie_df.iloc[:,j])
        corr_matrix[i, j] = r
        corr_matrix[j, i] = r
        p_values[i, j] = p
        p_values[j, i] = p

figure = plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))
corrplot(corr_matrix, p_values, randhie_df.columns)

  • We download the country GDP data from http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NY.GDP.PCAP.PP.CD.

  • This is the per capita GDP at Purchasing Power Parity (PPP).

  • The previous graph can be improved.

  • We can change the labels on the x axis to show thousands.

  • More importantly, we can change the x axis to run on a logarithmic scale.

In [27]:
from matplotlib.ticker import FuncFormatter

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))
plt.scatter(x=pop_lex_gdp_countries_df['2013_gdp'], 
            y=pop_lex_gdp_countries_df['2013_lex'], 
            s=0.000005*pop_lex_gdp_countries_df['2013'],
            alpha=0.5)
plt.xscale("log")

formatter = FuncFormatter(lambda v, p: "%dK" % (v / 1000))

plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(formatter)

  • As a further improvement, we would like to group the data based on the region of each country.

  • To do that, first we'll get a list of the regions and we'll create a region mapping from region names to integer values.

In [28]:
regions = pop_lex_gdp_countries_df['Region'].drop_duplicates()
print(regions)
regions_map = {v: k for k, v in enumerate(regions)}
print(regions_map)

  • We'll use the region mapping to add a Region Code column in our dataset.
In [29]:
pop_lex_gdp_countries_df['Region Code'] = pop_lex_gdp_countries_df['Region'].map(regions_map)
region_codes = pop_lex_gdp_countries_df['Region Code'].drop_duplicates()

  • Now we can create a plot that includes the region information, as a color dimension.

  • Note that we have to create the legend manually.

  • That's because we plotted everything in one go.

  • If we would like to have the legend created automatically, we should plot each region separately.

In [30]:
import matplotlib.patches as mpatches
import matplotlib.colors
import matplotlib.ticker

plt.style.use('seaborn-whitegrid')


plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))
plt.scatter(x=pop_lex_gdp_countries_df['2014_gdp'], 
            y=pop_lex_gdp_countries_df['2014_lex'], 
            s=0.000005*pop_lex_gdp_countries_df['2014'],
            c=pop_lex_gdp_countries_df['Region Code'],
            alpha=1,
            cmap='Paired')

plt.xscale("log")

recs = []

cmap = plt.get_cmap('Paired')

norm = matplotlib.colors.Normalize(0.0, 6.0)
for rc in region_codes:
    recs.append(mpatches.Rectangle((0,0),1,1, 
                                   fc=cmap(norm(rc))))
plt.legend(recs, regions, loc='lower right')
plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(formatter)
